      <hedline>
        <hl1>California Drug Model</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Dr Mitchell S Rosenthal, president of Phoenix House, cites organization's high rate of success in efforts to divert nonviolent drug offenders from incarceration to treatment (April 10 editorial)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Victory for California'' (editorial, April 10):</p>
        <p>Your editorial rightly praises California's continuing effort, commonly known as Proposition 36, to divert nonviolent drug offenders from incarceration to community-based drug treatment.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Victory for California'' (editorial, April 10):</p>
        <p>Your editorial rightly praises California's continuing effort, commonly known as Proposition 36, to divert nonviolent drug offenders from incarceration to community-based drug treatment.</p>
        <p>With evidence from the University of California at Los Angeles study that the program is cost-effective, it's time for other states to follow suit.</p>
        <p>They'll be saving money and saving lives.</p>
        <p>What we have seen at Phoenix House in California is what we have been able to show elsewhere, that coerced treatment works, and that with the right kind of treatment, even the most troubled and troublesome drug abusers are capable of changing their lives.</p>
        <p>Proposition 36 has brought some 500 drug law offenders to Phoenix House, most of whom would have never otherwise received treatment. But we have found them just as receptive, and as likely to succeed, as any other program participants.</p>
        <p>Mitchell S. Rosenthal, M.D.  President  Phoenix House  New York, April 10, 2006</p>
      </block>
